        "title": "Regex - Skip one or more lines",
        "body": "<p>I have the following <code>String<\/code> that I need to parse. I am looking for the <code>Board State<\/code> for each <code>Slot<\/code> number. <\/p>\n\n<pre><code>Some lines...\nSLOT  2 (RP/LC 2): Random Text\n   MAIN:\n   PCA:\n... More text\nBoard State is Val\n... More text\n\nSome lines...\nSLOT  3 (RP/LC 3): Random Text\n   MAIN:\n   PCA:\n... More text\nBoard State is Val2\n... More text\nsubslot 0/9/0\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Currently I have this. <\/p>\n\n<pre><code>String regex = \"(^SLOT\\\\s*\\\\d+).*\\\\s*.*\\\\s*.*\\\\s*.*\\\\s*.*\\\\s*.*\\\\s*.*\\\\s*.*\\\\s*.*\\\\s*.*\\\\s*.*\\\\s*.*\\\\s*.*\\\\s*.*\\\\s*.*\\\\s*.*\\\\s*.*\\\\s*.*\\\\s*(Board.*)\";\nPattern pattern = Pattern.compile(regex);\nMatcher matcher = pattern.matcher(commandOutput);\n\nwhile(matcher.find()) {\n     //Do Something\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>I am hard coding the number of lines it needs to skip but I don't like this and it's bad programming.<\/p>\n\n<p>Is it possible to do something like<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>regex = \"(^SLOT\\\\s*\\\\d+)(.*\\\\s*)+(Board.*)\"; //This obviously doesn't work. Find slot, then skip one or more lines until it finds Board. I am using \\\\s instead of \\\\r\\\\n because \\\\s skips tabs as well. \n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Edit: As to precisely what I want from the regex. Put <code>SLOT #<\/code> in a group and the <code>Board State is Val<\/code> in another group for all the <code>SLOTS<\/code>.<\/p>\n",
